author: @dennis8213
text: The script has been updated.  Now you can set the path of your image directory in the python3 command. It would look sth like that: "python3 generate_tfrecord.py --csv_input=data/train_labels.csv  --output_path=data/train.record --image_dir=images/train/"  And if you are using the newer version of Tensorflow, some parts have to be updated:  - The removed tf.app, so you have to build your FLAGS with the open source library, which looks very similar: https://abseil.io/docs/python/guides/flags  - For the other errors that will occur, just update tf to tf.compat.v1, example: tf.gfile.GFile() becomes tf.compat.v1.gfile.GFile(......)  tf.python_io.TFRecordWriter(FLAGS.output_path) becomes tf.compat.v1.python_io.TFRecordWriter(FLAGS.output_path)  And don't forget to update the last row to "app.run(main)" instead of "tf.app.run()"  I hope this helps!!

author: @whoisjohngalt1942
text: If you're using Tensorflow 2.0 you will get errors saying things like Attributeerror: module tensorflow has no attribute 'app'.  File "generate_tfrecords.py", line 23, in <module>. You will need to make the following changes in generate_tfrecord.py:  tf.app.flags > tf.compat.v1.flags tf.gfile.GFile > tf.io.gfile.GFile tf.python_io.TFRecordWriter > tf.compat.v1.python_io.TFRecordWrite tf.app.run() >  tf.compat.v1.app.run()

author: @janefan1227
text: I was using labelimg v.1.2 prebuilt binary for windows (https://tzutalin.github.io/labelImg/ ). It seems to generate the xml differently. In particular the <filename> tag contains only the filename, no extension. This caused generate_tfrecord to fail because it didn't find the path to the image. I changed root.find('filename') to root.find('path') in xml_to_csv. Hopes this helps someone. Only issue is that path is a absolute path so you'll probably need to re-run the scripts if you move the folder
